did.abstract: The 1925 F Street Club was one of the most exclusive social clubs in Washington, D.C. during the 20th century. This collection contains, guest lists, correspondences, financial records, operational records, event documents, and publicity materials of the club. The materials in the collection range in dates from circa 1933-circa 1999.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The materials are divided into five series: Financial Records, Club Management Documents, Club Events, Publicity, and Materials from Dr. Richard H. "Dick" Howland.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The F Street Club was once called "the hardest door in Washington to open" because of its elite status as the premier social club in the district. The private social club was started in 1933 by Laura Merriam Curtis Gross and was managed by Gross until her death in 1973. Gross was the uncrowned queen of the Republican party during her lifetime, so many of the clubs were powerful members of that party. However, in the later part of the twentieth century, more and more people of the Democratic party joined the club as well.

The club could accommodate about 48 people for dinner, and it became renowned for its intimate setting. Presidents such as Gerald Ford and Ronald Reagan held parties at the club, and many more influential Washingtonians hosted and attended functions at the club.

Before becoming the F Street Club, the house was originally built for U.S. Navy Admiral, Charles Steedman in 1849. Its next owner was local businessman, Alexander Ray, whose family owned the house from 1868 until it was purchased by American University around 1920 to be used a downtown campus for the institution. When those plans did not quickly come to fruition, the university rented the house to Mrs. Gross who lived in it for a little over ten years before transforming it into the famous social club. The George Washington University purchased the house from American University, which still officially owned the property, in 1974; however, it continued to lease the property to the club. In 1999, the club disbanded, and the house became the Alumni House for GWU. President Knapp, the university's president, moved into the house in 2008, and it remains the official residence of the president of GWU.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection contains correspondence, meeting minutes, personnel files, financial records, programs, brochures, menus, photographs, guest dining schedules, and publicity materials. The material dates from 1933-1999. These are the records of the 1925 F Street Club, a prominent social club in Washington, D.C. during the twentieth century.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Exact acquisition date and source are unknown, although it is believed that most of this collection came to the archives in 2008 when the building was turned into the President's Residence. (Previously accession 751)
The acquisition date and source for Series 5 is unknown.

physdesc.extent: Files in this series are located in two document boxes, one record center box, and one flat box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains materials related to the managment of the club. Files include materials that refer to topics like board meetings, memberships lists, correspondences between the club and its members, the physical club and its maintenance, and guest attendance calnedars. These materials are from circa 1939 to circa 1999. These are part of the records of the 1925 F Street Club, a prominent social club in Washington, D.C. during the twentieth century.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The materials in this series relate to the financials of the 1925 F Street Club. Materials included are account audit reports, club account balance sheets, asset and spending reports, and house charges. The materials range in date from circa 1939 to circa 1999. These are part of the records of the 1925 F Street Club, a prominent social club in Washington, D.C. during the twentieth century.

Matierals include menus, seating charts, photographs, programs, and correspondences regarding certain events. The matierals range in date from circa 1939 to circa 1999. These are part of the records of the 1925 F Street Club, a prominent social club in Washington, D.C. during the twentieth century.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The materials in this series pertain to the publicity of the club. Files includes materials such as photographs of staff and members, correspondences with the National Club Association and other clubs nationwide, articles about the club or related clubs in news outlets like the Washington Post or The Washingtonian. Materials in this series range in dates from circa 1939 to circa 1999. These are part of the records of the 1925 F Street Club, a prominent social club in Washington, D.C. during the twentieth century.

did.unittitle: Materials from Dr. Richard H. "Dick" Howland

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The acquisition of the materials in this series is unknown, but they appear to have belonged to Richard H. "Dick" Howland. They were discovered in a Gelman Library office in 2017.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of materials that appear to have been generated and collected by Dr. Richard H. "Dick" Howland during his association with the 1925 F. Street Club. They concern sales of items that were in the house, general club history, and the transition of the property to GW.
